[normal]Fact 2. A biodegradable carrier bag manufactured using Enzymoplast will pose no risk plastic film or bag recycling in the UK and or recyclers overseas.
[normal]4.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A positive message can continue to reduce, reuse and recycle carrier bags that contain Enzymoplast biodegradable master batch.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The majority of carrier bags are reused either for shopping or for a secondary purpose; the term single-use is misleading.
[normal]5.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Only a small percentage of carrier bags are recycled due to:
[normal]a)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Many carrier bags are reused for a secondary purpose such as bin liners. A study in Wales and Scotland estimated this be as much as 50%
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]For retailers, there can be a lack of recycling facilities and no communicated message about recycling carrier bags and communication
[normal]c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Lack of facilities around the UK and home-recycling collection facilities
[normal]Fact 3. A carrier bag that is made with Enzymoplast can be recycled with no cross-contamination of recycled feed-stock.
[normal]Fact 4. A carrier bag that is made with Enzymoplast technology will fall into the government’s legislative framework for a biodegradable bag to be exempt. The six requirements are:
[normal]a)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Fit for purpose
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Reused
[normal]c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Recycled
[normal]d)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Safely biodegrade
[normal]e)
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Will not generate methane in landfill
[normal]f)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]  Will cost little or no more than ordinary plastic bags
[normal]Fact 5. Over 80% of marine littering comes from land. The rest is mainly from fish
[normal]ing. 
[normal]A carrier bag containing Enzymoplast will be in contact with soil first and the biodegradable reaction will start. Once the reaction has started, it will continue in the event the bag enters a marine environment. The bag wills biodegrade safely with no contamination to the marine environment.
[normal]Fact 6. Carrier bags made with 50% recycled material with Enzymoplast will biodegrade safely and can be recycled. This is providing the 50% recycled material is from a known source with no contamination. 
[normal]Fact 7. Under the proposed exemptions a carrier bag made with Enzymoplast will be ‘Biodegradable’ and not ‘Oxo-degradable’. The term Oxo-Biodegradable is misleading.
[normal]6.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is concern within the packaging industry on the tender that was issued by DEFRA “Biodegradable Plastic Carrier Bags – Solutions through Innovation”. 
[normal]An award was made by DEFRA in January 2014 to two companies to complete their research by 31
[normal]st
[normal] March 2014. Under the framework, the government seeks to have a clearer indication for exemptions and biodegradable technologies. Contracts given to two companies will not give enough scope to make a final decision.
[normal]7.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Evidence presented to the Environmental Audit Committee on the 18
[normal]th
[normal] December 2013 shows that there would be a negative impact on jobs from the suppliers of carrier bags. An exempted biodegradable carrier bag will protect the packaging suppliers, securing jobs in the UK although it is noted that there would still be a likely fall in bag consumption.
[normal]7.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Evidence was heard on the 9
[normal]th
[normal] January 2014 at Environmental Audit Committee that exempting a carrier bag with Biodegradable technology would cost the recycling industry thousands of jobs. A Biodegradable carrier bag made with Enzymoplast will safeguard jobs in the recycling industry and ensure that there is continued feedsto
[normal]ck of plastic bags to recycle. 
[normal]8.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]An imposed levy on carrier bags is expected to reduce the usage by 85%. The reduction will cost the packaging industry hundreds of millions of pounds in lost revenue from the sale of plastic bags. This will put UK packaging suppliers out of business that invest in innovation and skills. There will be direct losses to H M Treasury in corporation taxes, import VAT, duty and VAT on the sale of the plastic bags from the packaging suppliers to retailers. The losses to H M Treasure will equate to tens of millions of pounds.
